[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In computer science and operations research, the **ant colony optimization** algorithm (**ACO**) is a probabilistic technique for solving computational problems that can be reduced to finding good paths through graphs.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Artificial ants represent multi-agent methods inspired by the behavior of real ants.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The pheromone-based communication of biological ants is often the predominant paradigm used.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Combinations of artificial ants and local search algorithms have become a preferred method for numerous optimization tasks involving some sort of graph, e.g., vehicle routing and internet routing.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] As an example, ant colony optimization is a class of optimization algorithms modeled on the actions of an ant colony.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Artificial 'ants' (e.g. simulation agents) locate optimal solutions by moving through a parameter space representing all possible solutions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Real ants lay down pheromones to direct each other to resources while exploring their environment.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The simulated 'ants' similarly, record their positions and the quality of their solutions so that in later simulation iterations more ants locate better solutions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] One variation on this approach is the bees algorithm, which is more analogous to the foraging patterns of the honey bee, another social insect.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This algorithm is a member of the ant colony algorithms family, in swarm intelligence methods, and it constitutes some metaheuristic optimizations.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Initially proposed by Marco Dorigo in 1992 in his PhD thesis, the first algorithm was aiming to search for an optimal path in a graph, based on the behavior of ants seeking a path between their colony and a source of food.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The original idea has since diversified to solve a wider class of numerical problems, and as a result, several problems have emerged, drawing on various aspects of the behavior of ants.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] From a broader perspective, ACO performs a model-based search and shares some similarities with estimation of distribution algorithms.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In the natural world, ants of some species (initially) wander randomly, and upon finding food return to their colony while laying down pheromone trails.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] If other ants find such a path, they are likely to stop travelling at random and instead follow the trail, returning and reinforcing it if they eventually find food (see Ant communication).
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Over time, however, the pheromone trail starts to evaporate, thus reducing its attractive strength.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The more time it takes for an ant to travel down the path and back again, the more time the pheromones have to evaporate.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] A short path, by comparison, is marched over more frequently, and thus the pheromone density becomes higher on shorter paths than longer ones.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Pheromone evaporation also has the advantage of avoiding the convergence to a locally optimal solution.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] If there were no evaporation at all, the paths chosen by the first ants would tend to be excessively attractive to the following ones.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In that case, the exploration of the solution space would be constrained.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The influence of pheromone evaporation in real ant systems is unclear, but it is very important in artificial systems.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The overall result is that when one ant finds a good (i.e., short) path from the colony to a food source, other ants are more likely to follow that path, and positive feedback eventually leads to many ants following a single path.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The idea of the ant colony algorithm is to mimic this behavior with "simulated ants" walking around the graph representing the problem to be solved.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] New concepts are required since "intelligence" is no longer centralized but can be found throughout all minuscule objects.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Anthropocentric concepts have been known to lead to the production of IT systems in which data processing, control units and calculating power are centralized.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] These centralized units have continually increased their performance and can be compared to the human brain.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The model of the brain has become the ultimate vision of computers.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Ambient networks of intelligent objects and, sooner or later, a new generation of information systems that are even more diffused and based on nanotechnology, will profoundly change this concept.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Small devices that can be compared to insects do not possess a high intelligence on their own.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Indeed, their intelligence can be classed as fairly limited.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] It is, for example, impossible to integrate a high performance calculator with the power to solve any kind of mathematical problem into a biochip that is implanted into the human body or integrated in an intelligent tag designed to trace commercial articles.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] However, once those objects are interconnected they develop a form of intelligence that can be compared to a colony of ants or bees.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In the case of certain problems, this type of intelligence can be superior to the reasoning of a centralized system similar to the brain.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Nature offers several examples of how minuscule organisms, if they all follow the same basic rule, can create a form of collective intelligence on the macroscopic level.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Colonies of social insects perfectly illustrate this model which greatly differs from human societies.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This model is based on the cooperation of independent units with simple and unpredictable behavior.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] They move through their surrounding area to carry out certain tasks and only possess a very limited amount of information to do so.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] A colony of ants, for example, represents numerous qualities that can also be applied to a network of ambient objects.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Colonies of ants have a very high capacity to adapt themselves to changes in the environment, as well as great strength in dealing with situations where one individual fails to carry out a given task.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This kind of flexibility would also be very useful for mobile networks of objects which are perpetually developing.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Parcels of information that move from a computer to a digital object behave in the same way as ants would do.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] They move through the network and pass from one node to the next with the objective of arriving at their final destination as quickly as possible.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Pheromone-based communication is one of the most effective ways of communication which is widely observed in nature.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Pheromone is used by social insects such as bees, ants and termites; both for inter-agent and agent-swarm communications.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Due to its feasibility, artificial pheromones have been adopted in multi-robot and swarm robotic systems.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Pheromone-based communication was implemented by different means such as chemical or physical (RFID tags, light, sound) ways.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] However, those implementations were not able to replicate all the aspects of pheromones as seen in nature.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Using projected light was presented in a 2007 IEEE paper by Garnier, Simon, et al. as an experimental setup to study pheromone-based communication with micro autonomous robots.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Another study presented a system in which pheromones were implemented via a horizontal LCD screen on which the robots moved, with the robots having downward facing light sensors to register the patterns beneath them.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In the ant colony optimization algorithms, an artificial ant is a simple computational agent that searches for good solutions to a given optimization problem.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] To apply an ant colony algorithm, the optimization problem needs to be converted into the problem of finding the shortest path on a weighted graph.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In the first step of each iteration, each ant stochastically constructs a solution, i.e. the order in which the edges in the graph should be followed.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In the second step, the paths found by the different ants are compared.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The last step consists of updating the pheromone levels on each edge.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Each ant needs to construct a solution to move through the graph.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] To select the next edge in its tour, an ant will consider the length of each edge available from its current position, as well as the corresponding pheromone level.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] At each step of the algorithm, each ant moves from a state x to state y , corresponding to a more complete intermediate solution.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Thus, each ant k computes a set $A_{k}(x)$ of feasible expansions to its current state in each iteration, and moves to one of these in probability.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The *trail level* represents a posteriori indication of the desirability of that move.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Trails are usually updated when all ants have completed their solution, increasing or decreasing the level of trails corresponding to moves that were part of "good" or "bad" solutions, respectively.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] where $L_{k}$ is the cost of the k th ant's tour (typically length) and Q is a constant.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Here are some of the most popular variations of ACO algorithms.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The ant system is the first ACO algorithm.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This algorithm corresponds to the one presented above.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] At the end of each iteration, only the best ant is allowed to update the trails by applying a modified global pheromone updating rule.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In this algorithm, the global best solution deposits pheromone on its trail after every iteration (even if this trail has not been revisited), along with all the other ants.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The elitist strategy has as its objective directing the search of all ants to construct a solution to contain links of the current best route.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This algorithm controls the maximum and minimum pheromone amounts on each trail.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Only the global best tour or the iteration best tour are allowed to add pheromone to its trail.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] To avoid stagnation of the search algorithm, the range of possible pheromone amounts on each trail is limited to an interval [τmax,τmin].
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] All edges are initialized to τmax to force a higher exploration of solutions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The trails are reinitialized to τmax when nearing stagnation.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] All solutions are ranked according to their length.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Only a fixed number of the best ants in this iteration are allowed to update their trials.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The amount of pheromone deposited is weighted for each solution, such that solutions with shorter paths deposit more pheromone than the solutions with longer paths.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] An ant colony system (ACS) with communication strategies is developed.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The artificial ants are partitioned into several groups.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Seven communication methods for updating the pheromone level between groups in ACS are proposed and work on the traveling salesman problem.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The pheromone deposit mechanism of COAC is to enable ants to search for solutions collaboratively and effectively.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] By using an orthogonal design method, ants in the feasible domain can explore their chosen regions rapidly and efficiently, with enhanced global search capability and accuracy.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The orthogonal design method and the adaptive radius adjustment method can also be extended to other optimization algorithms for delivering wider advantages in solving practical problems.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] It is a recursive form of ant system which divides the whole search domain into several sub-domains and solves the objective on these subdomains.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The results from all the subdomains are compared and the best few of them are promoted for the next level.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The subdomains corresponding to the selected results are further subdivided and the process is repeated until an output of desired precision is obtained.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This method has been tested on ill-posed geophysical inversion problems and works well.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] For some versions of the algorithm, it is possible to prove that it is convergent (i.e., it is able to find the global optimum in finite time).
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The first evidence of convergence for an ant colony algorithm was made in 2000, the graph-based ant system algorithm, and later on for the ACS and MMAS algorithms.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Like most metaheuristics, it is very difficult to estimate the theoretical speed of convergence.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In 2004, Zlochin and his colleagues showed that ACO-type algorithms are closely related to stochastic gradient descent, Cross-entropy method and estimation of distribution algorithm.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] They proposed an umbrella term "Model-based search" to describe this class of metaheuristics.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] It has also been used to produce near-optimal solutions to the travelling salesman problem.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] They have an advantage over simulated annealing and genetic algorithm approaches of similar problems when the graph may change dynamically; the ant colony algorithm can be run continuously and adapt to changes in real time.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This is of interest in network routing and urban transportation systems.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The first ACO algorithm was called the ant system and it was aimed to solve the travelling salesman problem, in which the goal is to find the shortest round-trip to link a series of cities.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The general algorithm is relatively simple and based on a set of ants, each making one of the possible round-trips along the cities.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] After each iteration, trails of pheromones evaporate.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] To optimize the form of antennas, ant colony algorithms can be used.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The ACO algorithm is used in image processing for image edge detection and edge linking.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The graph here is the 2-D image and the ants traverse from one pixel depositing pheromone.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The movement of ants from one pixel to another is directed by the local variation of the image's intensity values.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This movement causes the highest density of the pheromone to be deposited at the edges.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] There are various methods to determine the heuristic matrix.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] For the below example the heuristic matrix was calculated based on the local statistics: the local statistics at the pixel position $(i,j)$ .
