[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] With an ACO algorithm, the shortest path in a graph, between two points A and B, is built from a combination of several paths.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] It is not easy to give a precise definition of what algorithm is or is not an ant colony, because the definition may vary according to the authors and uses.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Broadly speaking, ant colony algorithms are regarded as populated metaheuristics with each solution represented by an ant moving in the search space.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Ants mark the best solutions and take account of previous markings to optimize their search.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] They can be seen as probabilistic multi-agent algorithms using a probability distribution to make the transition between each iteration.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In their versions for combinatorial problems, they use an iterative construction of solutions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] According to some authors, the thing which distinguishes ACO algorithms from other relatives (such as algorithms to estimate the distribution or particle swarm optimization) is precisely their constructive aspect.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In combinatorial problems, it is possible that the best solution eventually be found, even though no ant would prove effective.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Thus, in the example of the travelling salesman problem, it is not necessary that an ant actually travels the shortest route: the shortest route can be built from the strongest segments of the best solutions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] However, this definition can be problematic in the case of problems in real variables, where no structure of 'neighbours' exists.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The collective behaviour of social insects remains a source of inspiration for researchers.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The wide variety of algorithms (for optimization or not) seeking self-organization in biological systems has led to the concept of "swarm intelligence", which is a very general framework in which ant colony algorithms fit.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] There is in practice a large number of algorithms claiming to be "ant colonies", without always sharing the general framework of optimization by canonical ant colonies.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In practice, the use of an exchange of information between ants via the environment (a principle called "stigmergy") is deemed enough for an algorithm to belong to the class of ant colony algorithms.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This principle has led some authors to create the term "value" to organize methods and behavior based on search of food, sorting larvae, division of labour and cooperative transportation.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] These maintain a pool of solutions rather than just one.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The process of finding superior solutions mimics that of evolution, with solutions being combined or mutated to alter the pool of solutions, with solutions of inferior quality being discarded.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] that substitutes traditional reproduction operators by model-guided operators.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] A related global optimization technique which traverses the search space by generating neighboring solutions of the current solution.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] An inferior neighbor is accepted probabilistically based on the difference in quality and a temperature parameter.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The temperature parameter is modified as the algorithm progresses to alter the nature of the search.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Focuses on combining machine learning with optimization, by adding an internal feedback loop to self-tune the free parameters of an algorithm to the characteristics of the problem, of the instance, and of the local situation around the current solution.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Similar to simulated annealing in that both traverse the solution space by testing mutations of an individual solution.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] While simulated annealing generates only one mutated solution, tabu search generates many mutated solutions and moves to the solution with the lowest fitness of those generated.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] To prevent cycling and encourage greater movement through the solution space, a tabu list is maintained of partial or complete solutions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] It is forbidden to move to a solution that contains elements of the tabu list, which is updated as the solution traverses the solution space.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] A method that make use of clustering approach, extending the ACO.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] An agent-based probabilistic global search and optimization technique best suited to problems where the objective function can be decomposed into multiple independent partial-functions.
