[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Combinatorial optimization is related to operations research, algorithm theory, and computational complexity theory.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] It has important applications in several fields, including artificial intelligence, machine learning, auction theory, software engineering, VLSI, applied mathematics and theoretical computer science.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] There is a large amount of literature on polynomial-time algorithms for certain special classes of discrete optimization.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] A considerable amount of it is unified by the theory of linear programming.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Some examples of combinatorial optimization problems that are covered by this framework are shortest paths and shortest-path trees, flows and circulations, spanning trees, matching, and matroid problems.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Combinatorial optimization problems can be viewed as searching for the best element of some set of discrete items; therefore, in principle, any sort of search algorithm or metaheuristic can be used to solve them.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] However, generic search algorithms are not guaranteed to find an optimal solution first, nor are they guaranteed to run quickly (in polynomial time).
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Since some discrete optimization problems are NP-complete, such as the traveling salesman (decision) problem, this is expected unless P=NP.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] For each combinatorial optimization problem, there is a corresponding decision problem that asks whether there is a feasible solution for some particular measure $m_{0}$ .
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] For example, if there is a graph G which contains vertices u and v , an optimization problem might be "find a path from u to v that uses the fewest edges".
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] This problem might have an answer of, say, 4.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] A corresponding decision problem would be "is there a path from u to v that uses 10 or fewer edges?" This problem can be answered with a simple 'yes' or 'no'.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] The field of approximation algorithms deals with algorithms to find near-optimal solutions to hard problems.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] The usual decision version is then an inadequate definition of the problem since it only specifies acceptable solutions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Even though we could introduce suitable decision problems, the problem is then more naturally characterized as an optimization problem.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] An *NP-optimization problem* (NPO) is a combinatorial optimization problem with the following additional conditions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Note that the below referred polynomials are functions of the size of the respective functions' inputs, not the size of some implicit set of input instances.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] This implies that the corresponding decision problem is in NP.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] In computer science, interesting optimization problems usually have the above properties and are therefore NPO problems.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] A problem is additionally called a P-optimization (PO) problem, if there exists an algorithm which finds optimal solutions in polynomial time.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Often, when dealing with the class NPO, one is interested in optimization problems for which the decision versions are NP-complete.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Note that hardness relations are always with respect to some reduction.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Due to the connection between approximation algorithms and computational optimization problems, reductions which preserve approximation in some respect are for this subject preferred than the usual Turing and Karp reductions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] An example of such a reduction would be L-reduction.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] For this reason, optimization problems with NP-complete decision versions are not necessarily called NPO-complete.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] An NPO problem is called *polynomially bounded* (PB) if, for every instance x and for every solution $y\in f(x)$ , the measure $m(x,y)$ is bounded by a polynomial function of the size of x .
[src:combinatorial-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] The class NPOPB is the class of NPO problems that are polynomially-bounded.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] In mathematical optimization, the **cutting-plane method** is any of a variety of optimization methods that iteratively refine a feasible set or objective function by means of linear inequalities, termed *cuts*.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Such procedures are commonly used to find integer solutions to mixed integer linear programming (MILP) problems, as well as to solve general, not necessarily differentiable convex optimization problems.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] The use of cutting planes to solve MILP was introduced by Ralph E.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Cutting plane methods for MILP work by solving a non-integer linear program, the linear relaxation of the given integer program.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] The theory of Linear Programming dictates that under mild assumptions (if the linear program has an optimal solution, and if the feasible region does not contain a line), one can always find an extreme point or a corner point that is optimal.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] The obtained optimum is tested for being an integer solution.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] If it is not, there is guaranteed to exist a linear inequality that *separates* the optimum from the convex hull of the true feasible set.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Finding such an inequality is the *separation problem*, and such an inequality is a *cut*.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] A cut can be added to the relaxed linear program.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Then, the current non-integer solution is no longer feasible to the relaxation.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] This process is repeated until an optimal integer solution is found.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Cutting-plane methods for general convex continuous optimization and variants are known under various names: Kelley's method, Kelley–Cheney–Goldstein method, and bundle methods.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] They are popularly used for non-differentiable convex minimization, where a convex objective function and its subgradient can be evaluated efficiently but usual gradient methods for differentiable optimization can not be used.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] This situation is most typical for the concave maximization of Lagrangian dual functions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Another common situation is the application of the Dantzig–Wolfe decomposition to a structured optimization problem in which formulations with an exponential number of variables are obtained.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Generating these variables on demand by means of delayed column generation is identical to performing a cutting plane on the respective dual problem.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Cutting planes were proposed by Ralph Gomory in the 1950s as a method for solving integer programming and mixed-integer programming problems.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] However, most experts, including Gomory himself, considered them to be impractical due to numerical instability, as well as ineffective because many rounds of cuts were needed to make progress towards the solution.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Things turned around when in the mid-1990s Gérard Cornuéjols and co-workers showed them to be very effective in combination with branch-and-bound (called branch-and-cut) and ways to overcome numerical instabilities.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Nowadays, all commercial MILP solvers use Gomory cuts in one way or another.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Gomory cuts are very efficiently generated from a simplex tableau, whereas many other types of cuts are either expensive or even NP-hard to separate.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Among other general cuts for MILP, most notably lift-and-project dominates Gomory cuts.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] where A is a matrix and b , c is a vector.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] The vector x is unknown and is to be found in order to maximize the objective while respecting the linear constraints.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] The method proceeds by first dropping the requirement that the xi be integers and solving the associated relaxed linear programming problem to obtain a basic feasible solution.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Geometrically, this solution will be a vertex of the convex polytope consisting of all feasible points.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] If this vertex is not an integer point then the method finds a hyperplane with the vertex on one side and all feasible integer points on the other.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] This is then added as an additional linear constraint to exclude the vertex found, creating a modified linear program.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] The new program is then solved and the process is repeated until an integer solution is found.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] where *xi* is a basic variable and the *xj'*s are the nonbasic variables (i.e. the basic solution which is an optimal solution to the relaxed linear program is $x_{i}={\bar {b}}_{i}$ and $x_{j}=0$ ).
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] We write coefficients ${\bar {b}}_{i}$ and ${\bar {a}}_{i,j}$ with a bar to denote the last tableau produced by the simplex method.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] These coefficients are different from the coefficients in the matrix A and the vector b.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Consider now a basic variable $x_{i}$ which is not an integer.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] For any integer point in the feasible region, the left side is an integer since all the terms $x_{i}$ , $x_{j}$ , $\lfloor {\bar {a}}_{i,j}\rfloor$ , $\lfloor {\bar {b}}_{i}\rfloor$ are integers.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] The right side of this equation is strictly less than 1: indeed, ${\bar {b}}_{i}-\lfloor {\bar {b}}_{i}\rfloor$ is strictly less than 1 while $-\sum _{j}({\bar {a}}_{i,j}-\lfloor {\bar {a}}_{i,j}\rfloor )x_{j}$ is negative.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Therefore the common value must be less than or equal to 0.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] must hold for any integer point in the feasible region.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] So the inequality above excludes the basic feasible solution and thus is a cut with the desired properties.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] More precisely, ${\bar {b}}_{i}-\lfloor {\bar {b}}_{i}\rfloor -\sum _{j}({\bar {a}}_{i,j}-\lfloor {\bar {a}}_{i,j}\rfloor )x_{j}$ is negative for any integer point in the feasible region, and strictly positive for the basic feasible (non integer) solution of the relaxed linear program.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Cutting plane methods are also applicable in nonlinear programming.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/cutting-plane-method] The underlying principle is to approximate the feasible region of a nonlinear (convex) program by a finite set of closed half spaces and to solve a sequence of approximating linear programs.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A **genetic algorithm** (**GA**) is a metaheuristic inspired by the process of natural selection that belongs to the larger class of evolutionary algorithms (EA) in computer science and operations research.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Genetic algorithms are commonly used to generate high-quality solutions to optimization and search problems via biologically inspired operators such as selection, crossover, and mutation.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Some examples of GA applications include optimizing decision trees for better performance, solving sudoku puzzles, hyperparameter optimization, and causal inference.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In a genetic algorithm, a population of candidate solutions (called individuals, creatures, organisms, or phenotypes) to an optimization problem is evolved toward better solutions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Each candidate solution has a set of properties (its chromosomes or genotype) which can be mutated and altered; traditionally, solutions are represented in binary as strings of 0s and 1s, but other encodings are also possible.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The evolution usually starts from a population of randomly generated individuals, and is an iterative process, with the population in each iteration called a *generation*.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In each generation, the fitness of every individual in the population is evaluated; the fitness is usually the value of the objective function in the optimization problem being solved.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The more fit individuals are stochastically selected from the current population, and each individual's genome is modified (recombined and possibly randomly mutated) to form a new generation.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The new generation of candidate solutions is then used in the next iteration of the algorithm.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Commonly, the algorithm terminates when either a maximum number of generations has been produced, or a satisfactory fitness level has been reached for the population.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] 2. a fitness function to evaluate the solution domain.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A standard representation of each candidate solution is as an array of bits (also called *bit set* or *bit string*).
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Arrays of other types and structures can be used in essentially the same way.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The main property that makes these genetic representations convenient is that their parts are easily aligned due to their fixed size, which facilitates simple crossover operations.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Variable length representations may also be used, but crossover implementation is more complex in this case.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Tree-like representations are explored in genetic programming and graph-form representations are explored in evolutionary programming; a mix of both linear chromosomes and trees is explored in gene expression programming.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Once the genetic representation and the fitness function are defined, a GA proceeds to initialize a population of solutions and then to improve it through repetitive application of the mutation, crossover, inversion and selection operators.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The population size depends on the nature of the problem, but typically contains hundreds or thousands of possible solutions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Often, the initial population is generated randomly, allowing the entire range of possible solutions (the search space).
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Occasionally, the solutions may be "seeded" in areas where optimal solutions are likely to be found or the distribution of the sampling probability tuned to focus in those areas of greater interest.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] During each successive generation, a portion of the existing population is selected to reproduce for a new generation.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Individual solutions are selected through a *fitness-based* process, where fitter solutions (as measured by a fitness function) are typically more likely to be selected.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Certain selection methods rate the fitness of each solution and preferentially select the best solutions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Other methods rate only a random sample of the population, as the former process may be very time-consuming.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The fitness function is defined over the genetic representation and measures the *quality* of the represented solution.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The fitness function is always problem-dependent.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] For instance, in the knapsack problem one wants to maximize the total value of objects that can be put in a knapsack of some fixed capacity.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A representation of a solution might be an array of bits, where each bit represents a different object, and the value of the bit (0 or 1) represents whether or not the object is in the knapsack.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Not every such representation is valid, as the size of objects may exceed the capacity of the knapsack.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The *fitness* of the solution is the sum of values of all objects in the knapsack if the representation is valid, or 0 otherwise.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The next step is to generate a second generation population of solutions from those selected, through a combination of genetic operators: crossover (also called recombination), and mutation.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] For each new solution to be produced, a pair of "parent" solutions is selected for breeding from the pool selected previously.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] By producing a "child" solution using the above methods of crossover and mutation, a new solution is created which typically shares many of the characteristics of its "parents".
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] New parents are selected for each new child, and the process continues until a new population of solutions of appropriate size is generated.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Although reproduction methods that are based on the use of two parents are more "biology inspired", some research suggests that more than two "parents" generate higher quality chromosomes.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] These processes ultimately result in the next generation population of chromosomes that is different from the initial generation.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Generally, the average fitness will have increased by this procedure for the population, since only the best organisms from the first generation are selected for breeding, along with a small proportion of less fit solutions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] These less fit solutions ensure genetic diversity within the genetic pool of the parents and therefore ensure the genetic diversity of the subsequent generation of children.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Opinion is divided over the importance of crossover versus mutation.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] There are many references in Fogel (2006) that support the importance of mutation-based search.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] It is worth tuning parameters such as the mutation probability, crossover probability and population size to find reasonable settings for the problem's complexity class being worked on.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A very small mutation rate may lead to genetic drift (which is non-ergodic in nature).
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A recombination rate that is too high may lead to premature convergence of the genetic algorithm.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A mutation rate that is too high may lead to loss of good solutions, unless elitist selection is employed.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] An adequate population size ensures sufficient genetic diversity for the problem at hand, but can lead to a waste of computational resources if set to a value larger than required.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In addition to the main operators above, other heuristics may be employed to make the calculation faster or more robust.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The *speciation* heuristic penalizes crossover between candidate solutions that are too similar; this encourages population diversity and helps prevent premature convergence to a less optimal solution.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This generational process is repeated until a termination condition has been reached.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Genetic algorithms are simple to implement, but their behavior is difficult to understand.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In particular, it is difficult to understand why these algorithms frequently succeed at generating solutions of high fitness when applied to practical problems.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A hypothesis that a genetic algorithm performs adaptation by implicitly and efficiently implementing this heuristic.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] [crossed over], and resampled to form strings of potentially higher fitness.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In a way, by working with these particular schemata [the building blocks], we have reduced the complexity of our problem; instead of building high-performance strings by trying every conceivable combination, we construct better and better strings from the best partial solutions of past samplings".
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] "Because highly fit schemata of low defining length and low order play such an important role in the action of genetic algorithms, we have already given them a special name: building blocks.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Despite the lack of consensus regarding the validity of the building-block hypothesis, it has been consistently evaluated and used as reference throughout the years.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Many estimation of distribution algorithms, for example, have been proposed in an attempt to provide an environment in which the hypothesis would hold.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Although good results have been reported for some classes of problems, skepticism concerning the generality and/or practicality of the building-block hypothesis as an explanation for GAs' efficiency still remains.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Indeed, there is a reasonable amount of work that attempts to understand its limitations from the perspective of estimation of distribution algorithms.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The simplest algorithm represents each chromosome as a bit string.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Typically, numeric parameters can be represented by integers, though it is possible to use floating point representations.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The floating point representation is natural to evolution strategies and evolutionary programming.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The notion of real-valued genetic algorithms has been offered but is really a misnomer because it does not really represent the building block theory that was proposed by John Henry Holland in the 1970s.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This theory is not without support though, based on theoretical and experimental results (see below).
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The basic algorithm performs crossover and mutation at the bit level.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Other variants treat the chromosome as a list of numbers which are indexes into an instruction table, nodes in a linked list, hashes, objects, or any other imaginable data structure.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Crossover and mutation are performed so as to respect data element boundaries.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] For most data types, specific variation operators can be designed.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Different chromosomal data types seem to work better or worse for different specific problem domains.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] When bit-string representations of integers are used, Gray coding is often employed.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In this way, small changes in the integer can be readily affected through mutations or crossovers.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This has been found to help prevent premature convergence at so-called *Hamming walls*, in which too many simultaneous mutations (or crossover events) must occur in order to change the chromosome to a better solution.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Other approaches involve using arrays of real-valued numbers instead of bit strings to represent chromosomes.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Results from the theory of schemata suggest that in general the smaller the alphabet, the better the performance, but it was initially surprising to researchers that good results were obtained from using real-valued chromosomes.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This was explained as the set of real values in a finite population of chromosomes as forming a *virtual alphabet* (when selection and recombination are dominant) with a much lower cardinality than would be expected from a floating point representation.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] An expansion of the Genetic Algorithm accessible problem domain can be obtained through more complex encoding of the solution pools by concatenating several types of heterogenously encoded genes into one chromosome.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This particular approach allows for solving optimization problems that require vastly disparate definition domains for the problem parameters.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] For instance, in problems of cascaded controller tuning, the internal loop controller structure can belong to a conventional regulator of three parameters, whereas the external loop could implement a linguistic controller (such as a fuzzy system) which has an inherently different description.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This particular form of encoding requires a specialized crossover mechanism that recombines the chromosome by section, and it is a useful tool for the modelling and simulation of complex adaptive systems, especially evolution processes.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Another important expansion of the Genetic Algorithm (GA) accessible solution space was driven by the need to make representations amenable to variable levels of knowledge about the solution states.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Variable-length representations were inspired by the observation that, in nature, evolution tends to progress from simpler organisms to more complex ones—suggesting an underlying rationale for embracing flexible structures.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A second, more pragmatic motivation was that most real-world engineering and knowledge-based problems do not naturally conform to rigid knowledge structures.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] These early innovations in variable-length representations laid essential groundwork for the development of Genetic programming, which further extended the classical GA paradigm.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Such representations required enhancements to the simplistic genetic operators used for fixed-length chromosomes, enabling the emergence of more sophisticated and adaptive GA models.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A practical variant of the general process of constructing a new population is to allow the best organism(s) from the current generation to carry over to the next, unaltered.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This strategy is known as *elitist selection* and guarantees that the solution quality obtained by the GA will not decrease from one generation to the next.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Parallel implementations of genetic algorithms come in two flavors.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Coarse-grained parallel genetic algorithms assume a population on each of the computer nodes and migration of individuals among the nodes.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Fine-grained parallel genetic algorithms assume an individual on each processor node which acts with neighboring individuals for selection and reproduction.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Other variants, like genetic algorithms for online optimization problems, introduce time-dependence or noise in the fitness function.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Genetic algorithms with adaptive parameters (adaptive genetic algorithms, AGAs) is another significant and promising variant of genetic algorithms.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The probabilities of crossover (pc) and mutation (pm) greatly determine the degree of solution accuracy and the convergence speed that genetic algorithms can obtain.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Researchers have analyzed GA convergence analytically.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Instead of using fixed values of *pc* and *pm*, AGAs utilize the population information in each generation and adaptively adjust the *pc* and *pm* in order to maintain the population diversity as well as to sustain the convergence capacity.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In AGA (adaptive genetic algorithm), the adjustment of *pc* and *pm* depends on the fitness values of the solutions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] There are more examples of AGA variants: Successive zooming method is an early example of improving convergence.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In *CAGA* (clustering-based adaptive genetic algorithm), through the use of clustering analysis to judge the optimization states of the population, the adjustment of *pc* and *pm* depends on these optimization states.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Recent approaches use more abstract variables for deciding *pc* and *pm*.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Examples are dominance & co-dominance principles and LIGA (levelized interpolative genetic algorithm), which combines a flexible GA with modified A* search to tackle search space anisotropicity.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] It can be quite effective to combine GA with other optimization methods.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A GA tends to be quite good at finding generally good global solutions, but quite inefficient at finding the last few mutations to find the absolute optimum.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Other techniques (such as simple hill climbing) are quite efficient at finding absolute optimum in a limited region.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Alternating GA and hill climbing can improve the efficiency of GA while overcoming the lack of robustness of hill climbing.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This means that the rules of genetic variation may have a different meaning in the natural case.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] For instance – provided that steps are stored in consecutive order – crossing over may sum a number of steps from maternal DNA adding a number of steps from paternal DNA and so on.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This is like adding vectors that more probably may follow a ridge in the phenotypic landscape.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Thus, the efficiency of the process may be increased by many orders of magnitude.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Moreover, the inversion operator has the opportunity to place steps in consecutive order or any other suitable order in favour of survival or efficiency.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A variation, where the population as a whole is evolved rather than its individual members, is known as gene pool recombination.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A number of variations have been developed to attempt to improve performance of GAs on problems with a high degree of fitness epistasis, i.e. where the fitness of a solution consists of interacting subsets of its variables.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Such algorithms aim to learn (before exploiting) these beneficial phenotypic interactions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] As such, they are aligned with the Building Block Hypothesis in adaptively reducing disruptive recombination.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Prominent examples of this approach include the mGA, GEMGA and LLGA.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Problems which appear to be particularly appropriate for solution by genetic algorithms include timetabling and scheduling problems, and many scheduling software packages are based on GAs.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] GAs have also been applied to engineering.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Genetic algorithms are often applied as an approach to solve global optimization problems.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] As a general rule of thumb genetic algorithms might be useful in problem domains that have a complex fitness landscape as mixing, i.e., mutation in combination with crossover, is designed to move the population away from local optima that a traditional hill climbing algorithm might get stuck in.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Observe that commonly used crossover operators cannot change any uniform population.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Mutation alone can provide ergodicity of the overall genetic algorithm process (seen as a Markov chain).
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In 1950, Alan Turing proposed a "learning machine" which would parallel the principles of evolution.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Computer simulation of evolution started as early as in 1954 with the work of Nils Aall Barricelli, who was using the computer at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] His 1954 publication was not widely noticed.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Starting in 1957, the Australian quantitative geneticist Alex Fraser published a series of papers on simulation of artificial selection of organisms with multiple loci controlling a measurable trait.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] From these beginnings, computer simulation of evolution by biologists became more common in the early 1960s, and the methods were described in books by Fraser and Burnell (1970) and Crosby (1973).
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Fraser's simulations included all of the essential elements of modern genetic algorithms.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In addition, Hans-Joachim Bremermann published a series of papers in the 1960s that also adopted a population of solution to optimization problems, undergoing recombination, mutation, and selection.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Bremermann's research also included the elements of modern genetic algorithms.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Other noteworthy early pioneers include Richard Friedberg, George Friedman, and Michael Conrad.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Many early papers are reprinted by Fogel (1998).
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Another approach was the evolutionary programming technique of Lawrence J.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Fogel, which was proposed for generating artificial intelligence.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Evolutionary programming originally used finite state machines for predicting environments, and used variation and selection to optimize the predictive logics.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Genetic algorithms in particular became popular through the work of John Holland in the early 1970s, and particularly his book *Adaptation in Natural and Artificial Systems* (1975).
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] His work originated with studies of cellular automata, conducted by Holland and his students at the University of Michigan.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Holland introduced a formalized framework for predicting the quality of the next generation, known as Holland's Schema Theorem.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Research in GAs remained largely theoretical until the mid-1980s, when The First International Conference on Genetic Algorithms was held in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In the late 1980s, General Electric started selling the world's first genetic algorithm product, a mainframe-based toolkit designed for industrial processes.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In 1989, Axcelis, Inc. released Evolver,the world's first commercial GA product for desktop computers.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The New York Times technology writer John Markoff wrote about Evolver in 1990, and it remained the only interactive commercial genetic algorithm until 1995.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Evolver was sold to Palisade in 1997, translated into several languages, and is currently in its 6th version.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Since the 1990s, MATLAB has built in three derivative-free optimization heuristic algorithms (simulated annealing, particle swarm optimization, genetic algorithm) and two direct search algorithms (simplex search, pattern search).
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Evolutionary algorithms is a sub-field of evolutionary computing.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Swarm intelligence is a sub-field of evolutionary computing.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Evolutionary computation is a sub-field of the metaheuristic methods.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Metaheuristic methods broadly fall within stochastic optimisation methods.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] In computer science, **local search** is a heuristic method for solving computationally hard optimization problems.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] Local search can be used on problems that can be formulated as finding a solution that maximizes a criterion among a number of candidate solutions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] Local search algorithms move from solution to solution in the space of candidate solutions (the *search space*) by applying local changes, until a solution deemed optimal is found or a time bound is elapsed.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] Local search algorithms are widely applied to numerous hard computational problems, including problems from computer science (particularly artificial intelligence), mathematics, operations research, engineering, and bioinformatics.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] Examples of local search algorithms are WalkSAT, the 2-opt algorithm for the traveling salesman problem and the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] While it is sometimes possible to substitute gradient descent for a local search algorithm, gradient descent is not in the same family: although it is an iterative method for local optimization, it relies on an objective function’s gradient rather than an explicit exploration of the solution space.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] The Hopfield Neural Networks problem involves finding stable configurations in Hopfield network.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] Most problems can be formulated in terms of a search space and target in several different ways.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] For example, for the traveling salesman problem a solution can be a route visiting all cities and the goal is to find the shortest route.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] But a solution can also be a path, and being a cycle is part of the target.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] A local search algorithm starts from a candidate solution and then iteratively moves to a neighboring solution; a neighborhood being the set of all potential solutions that differ from the current solution by the minimal possible extent.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] This requires a neighborhood relation to be defined on the search space.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] As an example, the neighborhood of vertex cover is another vertex cover only differing by one node.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] For Boolean satisfiability, the neighbors of a Boolean assignment are those that have a single variable in an opposite state.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] The same problem may have multiple distinct neighborhoods defined on it; local optimization with neighborhoods that involve changing up to *k* components of the solution is often referred to as **k-opt**.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] Typically, every candidate solution has more than one neighbor solution; the choice of which one to select is taken using only information about the solutions in the neighborhood of the current assignment, hence the name *local* search.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] When the choice of the neighbor solution is done by taking the one locally maximizing the criterion, i.e.: a greedy search, the metaheuristic takes the name hill climbing.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] When no improving neighbors are present, local search is stuck at a locally optimal point.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] Local search does not provide a guarantee that any given solution is optimal.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] The search can terminate after a given time bound or when the best solution found thus far has not improved in a given number of steps.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] Local search is an anytime algorithm; it can return a valid solution even if it's interrupted at any time after finding the first valid solution.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] Local search is typically an approximation or incomplete algorithm because the search may stop even if the current best solution found is not optimal.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] This can happen even if termination happens because the current best solution could not be improved, as the optimal solution can lie far from the neighborhood of the solutions crossed by the algorithm.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/local-search-optimization] They hypothesize that local search algorithms work well, not because they have some understanding of the search space but because they quickly move to promising regions, and explore the search space at low depths as quickly, broadly, and systematically as possible.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Similar techniques have been independently introduced on several occasions, including Pincus (1970), Khachaturyan et al.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] In 1983, this approach was used by Kirkpatrick, Gelatt Jr., and Vecchi for a solution of the traveling salesman problem.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] They also proposed its current name, simulated annealing.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] The name of the algorithm comes from annealing in metallurgy, a technique involving heating and controlled cooling of a material to alter its physical properties.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] This notion of slow cooling implemented in the simulated annealing algorithm is interpreted as a slow decrease in the probability of accepting worse solutions as the solution space is explored.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Accepting worse solutions allows for a more extensive search for the global optimal solution.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Simulated annealing algorithms work by progressively decreasing the temperature from an initial positive value to zero.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] At each time step, the algorithm randomly selects a solution close to the current one, measures its quality, and moves to it according to the temperature-dependent probabilities of selecting better or worse solutions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] The simulation can be performed either by a solution of kinetic equations for probability density functions, or by using a stochastic sampling method.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] The method is an adaptation of the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, a Monte Carlo method to generate sample states of a thermodynamic system, published by N.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] The state *s* of some physical systems, and the function *E*(*s*) to be minimized, is analogous to the internal energy of the system in that state.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] The goal is to bring the system, from an arbitrary *initial state*, to a state with the minimum possible energy.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] At each step, the simulated annealing heuristic considers some neighboring state *s** of the current state *s*, and probabilistically decides between moving the system to state *s** or staying in state *s*.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] These probabilities ultimately lead the system to move to states of lower energy.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Typically, this step is repeated until the system reaches a state that is good enough for the application, or until a given computation budget has been exhausted.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Optimization of a solution involves evaluating the neighbor states, which are new states produced through conservatively altering the current state.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] For example, in the traveling salesman problem, each state is typically defined as a permutation of the cities to be visited, and the neighbors of any state are the set of permutations produced by swapping any two of these cities.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] The well-defined way in which the states are altered to produce neighboring states is called a *move*, and different moves give different sets of neighboring states.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] These moves usually result in minimal alterations of the current state, in an attempt to progressively improve the solution through iteratively improving its parts (such as the city connections in the traveling salesman problem).
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Metaheuristics use the neighbors of a solution as a way to explore the solution space, and although they prefer better neighbors, they probabilistically also accept worse neighbors to avoid getting stuck in local optima; they can find the global optimum if given enough time.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] States with a smaller energy are better than those with a greater energy.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] The probability function P must be positive even when $e_{\mathrm {new} }$ is greater than e .
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] This feature prevents the method from becoming stuck at a local minimum that is worse than the global one.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] When T tends to zero, the probability $P(e,e_{\mathrm {new} },T)$ must tend to zero if $e_{\mathrm {new} }>e$ and to a positive value otherwise.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] For sufficiently small values of T , the system will then increasingly favor moves that go *downhill* (i.e., to lower energy values), and avoid those that go *uphill*.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] With $T=0$ the procedure reduces to the greedy algorithm, which makes only the downhill transitions.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] In the original description of simulated annealing, the probability $P(e,e_{\mathrm {new} },T)$ was equal to 1 when $e_{\mathrm {new} }<e$ —i.e., the procedure always moved downhill when it found a way to do so, irrespective of the temperature.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Many descriptions and implementations of simulated annealing still take this condition as part of the method's definition.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] However, this condition is not essential for the method to work.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] The P function is usually chosen so that the probability of accepting a move decreases when the difference $e_{\mathrm {new} }-e$ increases—that is, small uphill moves are more likely than large ones.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] However, this requirement is not strictly necessary, provided that the above requirements are met.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Given these properties, the temperature T plays a crucial role in controlling the evolution of the state s of the system with regard to its sensitivity to the variations of system energies.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] To be precise, for a large T , the evolution of s is sensitive to coarser energy variations, while it is sensitive to finer energy variations when T is small.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Example illustrating the effect of cooling schedule on the performance of simulated annealing.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] to attract at short range and repel at a slightly larger distance.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] The elementary moves swap two adjacent pixels.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] The name and inspiration of the algorithm demand controlled temperature variation.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] This necessitates a gradual reduction of the temperature as the simulation proceeds.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] The algorithm starts initially with T set to a high value, and then it is decreased at each step following some *annealing schedule*—which may be specified by the user but must end with $T=0$ towards the end of the allotted time budget.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] For any given finite problem, the probability that the simulated annealing algorithm terminates with a global optimal solution approaches 1 as the annealing schedule is extended.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] This theoretical result, however, is not particularly helpful, since the time required to ensure a significant probability of success will usually exceed the time required for a complete search of the solution space.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] The following pseudocode presents the simulated annealing heuristic as described above.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] It starts from a state *s*0 and continues until a maximum of *k*max steps have been taken.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] In the process, the call neighbour(*s*) should generate a randomly chosen neighbour of a given state s; the call random(0, 1) should pick and return a value in the range [0, 1], uniformly at random.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] The annealing schedule is defined by the call temperature(*r*), which should yield the temperature to use, given the fraction r of the time budget that has been expended so far.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] These choices can have a significant impact on the method's effectiveness.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Unfortunately, there are no choices of these parameters that will be good for all problems, and there is no general way to find the best choices for a given problem.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] The following sections give some general guidelines.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Simulated annealing may be modeled as a random walk on a search graph, whose vertices are all possible states, and the edges connecting the vertices are the candidate moves.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] An essential requirement for the neighbour() function is that it must provide a sufficiently short path on this graph from the initial state to any state that may be the global optimum – the diameter of the search graph must be small.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] To investigate the behavior of simulated annealing on a particular problem, it can be useful to consider the *transition probabilities* that result from the various design choices made in the implementation of the algorithm.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] For each edge $(s,s')$ of the search graph, the transition probability is defined as the probability that the simulated annealing algorithm will move to state $s'$ when its current state is s .
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] This probability depends on the current temperature as specified by temperature(), on the order in which the candidate moves are generated by the neighbour() function, and on the acceptance probability function P().
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Note that the transition probability is **not** simply $P(e,e',T)$ , because the candidates are tested serially.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] The specification of neighbour(), P(), and temperature() is partially redundant.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] In practice, it's common to use the same acceptance function P() for many problems and adjust the other two functions according to the specific problem.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] In the formulation of the method by Kirkpatrick et al., the acceptance probability function $P(e,e',T)$ was defined as 1 if $e'<e$ , and $\exp(-(e'-e)/T)$ otherwise.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] This formula was superficially justified by analogy with the transitions of a physical system; it corresponds to the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, in the case where T=1 and the proposal distribution of Metropolis–Hastings is symmetric.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] However, this acceptance probability is often used for simulated annealing even when the neighbour() function, which is analogous to the proposal distribution in Metropolis–Hastings, is not symmetric, or not probabilistic at all.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Nevertheless, most descriptions of simulated annealing assume the original acceptance function, which is probably hard-coded in many implementations of SA.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] In 1990, Moscato and Fontanari, and independently Dueck and Scheuer, proposed that a deterministic update (i.e. one that is not based on the probabilistic acceptance rule) could speed-up the optimization process without impacting on the final quality.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] In 2001, Franz, Hoffmann and Salamon showed that the deterministic update strategy is indeed the optimal one within the large class of algorithms that simulate a random walk on the cost/energy landscape.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] When choosing the candidate generator `neighbour()`, one must consider that after a few iterations of the simulated annealing algorithm, the current state is expected to have much lower energy than a random state.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Therefore, as a general rule, one should skew the generator towards candidate moves where the energy of the destination state $s'$ is likely to be similar to that of the current state.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] This heuristic (which is the main principle of the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm) tends to exclude *very good* candidate moves as well as *very bad* ones; however, the former are usually much less common than the latter, so the heuristic is generally quite effective.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] In the traveling salesman problem above, for example, swapping two *consecutive* cities in a low-energy tour is expected to have a modest effect on its energy (length); whereas swapping two *arbitrary* cities is far more likely to increase its length than to decrease it.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Thus, the consecutive-swap neighbor generator is expected to perform better than the arbitrary-swap one, even though the latter could provide a somewhat shorter path to the optimum (with $n-1$ swaps, instead of $n(n-1)/2$ ).
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] A more precise statement of the heuristic is that one should try the first candidate states $s'$ for which $P(E(s),E(s'),T)$ is large.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] For the "standard" acceptance function P above, it means that $E(s')-E(s)$ is on the order of T or less.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Thus, in the traveling salesman example above, one could use a `neighbour()` function that swaps two random cities, where the probability of choosing a city-pair vanishes as their distance increases beyond T .
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] When choosing the candidate generator `neighbour()` one must also try to reduce the number of "deep" local minima—states (or sets of connected states) that have much lower energy than all its neighboring states.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] As a rule, it is impossible to design a candidate generator that will satisfy this goal and also prioritize candidates with similar energy.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] On the other hand, one can often vastly improve the efficiency of simulated annealing by relatively simple changes to the generator.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] In this example, A and B lie in different "deep basins" if the generator performs only random pair-swaps; but they will be in the same basin if the generator performs random segment-flips.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] The physical analogy that is used to justify simulated annealing assumes that the cooling rate is low enough for the probability distribution of the current state to be near thermodynamic equilibrium at all times.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Unfortunately, the *relaxation time*—the time one must wait for the equilibrium to be restored after a change in temperature—strongly depends on the "topography" of the energy function and on the current temperature.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] In the simulated annealing algorithm, the relaxation time also depends on the candidate generator, in a very complicated way.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Note that all these parameters are usually provided as black box functions to the simulated annealing algorithm.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Therefore, the ideal cooling rate cannot be determined beforehand and should be empirically adjusted for each problem.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Adaptive simulated annealing algorithms address this problem by connecting the cooling schedule to the search progress.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Other adaptive approaches such as Thermodynamic Simulated Annealing, automatically adjusts the temperature at each step based on the energy difference between the two states, according to the laws of thermodynamics.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Sometimes it is better to move back to a solution that was significantly better rather than always moving from the current state.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] This process is called *restarting* of simulated annealing.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] To do this we set s and e to ${\text{sbest}}$ and ${\text{ebest}}$ and perhaps restart the annealing schedule.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] The decision to restart could be based on several criteria.
[src:combinatorial-optimization/simulated-annealing] Notable among these include restarting based on a fixed number of steps, based on whether the current energy is too high compared to the best energy obtained so far, restarting randomly, etc.
